The API 2 Documentation provides an incorrect example for the resource:

/rest/api/2/issue/{issueIdOrKey}
[http://docs.atlassian.com/jira/REST/5.1.2/#id75230]

The *watcher* field is documented to be in the format:

{code}
 "watcher": {
            "self": "http://www.example.com/jira/rest/api/2/issue/EX-1/watchers",
            "isWatching": false,
            "watchCount": 1,
            "watchers": [
                {
                    "self": "http://www.example.com/jira/rest/api/2/user?username=fred",
                    "name": "fred",
                    "avatarUrls": {
                        "16x16": "http://www.example.com/jira/secure/useravatar?size=small&ownerId=fred",
                        "48x48": "http://www.example.com/jira/secure/useravatar?size=large&ownerId=fred"
                    },
                    "displayName": "Fred F. User",
                    "active": false
                }
            ]
        },
{code}

Where as requests actually return:

{code}
"watches":{
        "self":"https://jira.zedcore.com:8443/rest/api/2/issue/SANDBOX-1/watchers",
        "watchCount":1,
        "isWatching":true
}
{code}

The documented version seems both more consistent with everything else, and also much more useful as it doesn't require a second GET request to find the watchers for an issue.

It would be much better if the API acted as documented for this field.


The *comment* field is documented as:
{code}
 "comment": [
            {
                "self": "http://www.example.com/jira/rest/api/2.0/issue/10010/comment/10000",
                "id": "10000",
                "author": {
                    "self": "http://www.example.com/jira/rest/api/2.0/user?username=fred",
                    "name": "fred",
                    "displayName": "Fred F. User",
                    "active": false
                },
                "body": "Lorem ipsum dolor sit amet, consectetur adipiscing elit. Pellentesque eget venenatis elit. Duis eu justo eget augue iaculis fermentum. Sed semper quam laoreet nisi egestas at posuere augue semper.",
                "updateAuthor": {
                    "self": "http://www.example.com/jira/rest/api/2.0/user?username=fred",
                    "name": "fred",
                    "displayName": "Fred F. User",
                    "active": false
                },
                "created": "2012-07-30T03:41:40.012-0500",
                "updated": "2012-07-30T03:41:40.012-0500",
                "visibility": {
                    "type": "role",
                    "value": "Administrators"
                }
            }
        ],
{code}

But a comment search resource is actually returned:
{code}
"comment":{
        "startAt":0,
        "maxResults":2,
        "total":2,
        "comments":[
                {
                "self":"https://jira.zedcore.com:8443/rest/api/2/issue/11308/comment/11545",
                "id":"11545",
                "author":{<user-resource-removed>},
                "body":"Test comment",
                "updateAuthor<user-resource-removed>},
                "created":"2012-09-07T12:49:29.874+0100",
                "updated":"2012-09-07T12:49:29.874+0100"
                },
        ]
}
{code}

The search definition isn't all that useful, but I can understand getting it so we know if only 50 comments of N are shown etc.
This probably just needs updating the documentation.


Thanks


Edit:
Another thing I've spotted:

*/rest/API/latest/priority* (http://docs.atlassian.com/jira/REST/latest/#id123902)

Documented as returning keys: ['self', 'statusColor', 'description', 'iconUrl', 'name'], 
It also returns the 'id' field in practice.

Another one:

*/rest/api/latest/issue/<IssueIDorKey>* (http://docs.atlassian.com/jira/REST/latest/#id128750)

Field 'priority' is returned for issue resources but not documented in example return data.

